        <section xml:id="sec-gen-cyclic-gp">
          <title>Generators and Cyclic Groups</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-groupgenerate">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A subset <m>S</m> of a group <m>G</m> is said to <em>generate</em> <m>G</m> if every element of <m>G</m> is equal to a product of elements of <m>S</m> and their inverses (with repetitions allowed). 
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Assume that the regular <m>n</m>-gon <m>P_n</m> is drawn in the plane with its center at the origin and one vertex on the <m>x</m> axis. If <m>r</m> denotes rotation about the origin by <m>\frac{2\pi}{n}</m> radians counter-clockwise, then <m>r \in D_{2n}</m>. It’s inverse is rotation by <m>2 \pi/n</m> clock-wise. For another example, for any line of symmetry of <m>P_n</m>, reflection about that line gives an element of <m>D_{2n}</m>. By our convention for how to draw <m>P_n</m>, the <m>x</m>-axis is a line of symmetry for <m>P_n</m>, and we let <m>s</m> denote reflection about the <m>x</m>-axis.
          </p>

          <problem>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove <m>|r|=n</m> and <m>|s|=2</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that <m>sr</m> is a reflection and hence that <m>srsr=1_{{\mathbb{R}}^2}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that <m>D_{2n}</m> is generated by <m>r</m> and any reflection. 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that if <m>p\ge 3</m> is prime then <m>D_{2p}</m> is generated by any two distinct reflections.               
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              For <m>n\ge 2</m> prove that <m>S_n</m> is generated by <m>(12)</m> and the <m>n</m>-cycle <m>(12\cdots n)</m>.
            </p>
          </problem>


          <subsection xml:id="subsec-cyclic-gp">
            <title>Cyclic Groups</title>
            
            <definition xml:id="def-cyclic-group">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>G</m> is a generated by a single element, i.e. <m>G   = \langle x \rangle</m> for some <m>x \in G</m>, then <m>G</m> is called a <em>cyclic group</em>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Let <m>G=\langle x\rangle</m> be a cyclic group. Then <m>G=\langle x^{-1}\rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <problem>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove <m>(\mathbb{Z},+)</m> is generated by <m>1</m> or <m>-1</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove <m>(\mathbb{Z}/(n),+)</m> is generated by <m>[a]_n</m> for any integer <m>a</m> such that <m>\operatorname{gcd}(a,n)=1</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </problem>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>(\mathbb Q, +)</m> is not a cyclic group.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-cyclicabelian">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Prove that any cyclic group is abelian.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>\operatorname{GL}_2(\mathbb Z/(2))</m> is not cyclic.
              </p>
            </problem>

          </subsection>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-subgroups">
          <title>Subgroups</title>
    
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-subgrp-defn-ex">
            <title>Definition and Examples</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-subgroup">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A nonempty subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is called a <em>subgroup</em> provided <m>H</m> is a group under the multiplication law of <m>G</m>. The fact that <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> is denoted <m>H\leq G</m> or <m>H&lt;G</m> if we also mean that <m>H\neq G</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-subgrouptest">
              <title>Subgroup Tests</title>
              
              
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and closed under multiplication and inversion, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and satisfies for all <m>x,y \in H</m>, <m>xy^{-1} \in H</m>, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>

            <example>
              <p>
                Prove the following:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\{e_G\}</m> and <m>G</m> are the <em>trivial subgroups</em> of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\Z\leq\Q\leq\R\leq\C</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\Z^\times\leq\Q^\times\leq\R^\times\leq\C^\times</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>n\in\N</m> and define <m>n\Z=\{x\in\Z|x=nk\;\text{for some}\;k\in\Z\}</m>. Prove <m>n\Z\leq\Z</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> and <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>H</m>, then <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> for all <m>\alpha</m> in an index set <m>J</m>, then <m>H=\bigcap_{\alpha\in J} H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>G</m> be a group. For any <m>g\in G</m>, prove that the set <m>Z_G(g)=\{x\in G|gx=xg\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </example>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>H</m>, <m>H'</m> subgroups. Prove that <m>H\cup H'</m> is a subgroup if and only if <m>H\subseteq H'</m> or <m>H'\subseteq H</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Let <m>H</m> be a [[Mathematics/Definitions/Subgroup|subgroup]] of <m>G</m> and fix some element <m>g\in G</m>. Prove that <m>gHg^{-1}=\{ghg^{-1} \mid h\in H\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> of the same [[Mathematics/Definitions/Order|order]] as <m>H</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <definition xml:id="def-altgroup">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The <em>alternating group</em> <m>A_n</m> is the subset of all even cycles of <m>S_n</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A_n</m> is a subgroup of <m>S_n</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <definition xml:id="def-slg">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  For any field <m>F</m>, the <em>special linear group</em>
                  <me>
                    \SL_n(F)=\{A \mid A = n\times n \;\text{matrix with entries in}\; F, \det(A)=1_F\}
                  </me>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>SL_n(F)</m> is a subgroup of <m>GL_n(F)</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>
            
          </subsection>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-center">
            <title>The Center of a Group</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-gpcenter">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The <em>center</em> of a group <m>G</m> often written <m>Z(G)</m>, is the set of elements of <m>G</m> that commute with every element of <m>G</m>. That is, 
                  <me>
                    Z(G)=\{x \in G \, | \, xy = yx\,\text{ for all $y \in G$}\}.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>Z(G)</m> is an abelian subgroup for any group <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>
            

            <problem>
              <p>
                Find <m>Z(D_{2n})</m> for <m>n \geq 3</m>. Your answer will depend on whether <m>n</m> is even or odd.
              </p>
            </problem>


          </subsection>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-gensubgp">
            <title>Generated Subgroups</title>


            <definition xml:id="def-gensubgp">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Given a group <m>G</m> and a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the <em>subgroup of <m>G</m> generated by <m>X</m></em> is <me>\langle X \rangle := \bigcap_{H \leq G, H \supseteq X} H.</me> If <m>X=\{x\}</m> is a set with one element then we write <m>\langle X \rangle=\langle x \rangle</m> and we refer to this as the <em>cyclic subgroup generated by</em> <m>x</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>


            <lemma xml:id="lem-gensubgp">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  For a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the elements of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> can be described as: <me>\langle X \rangle = \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}.</me>
                </p>
              </statement>

              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>S= \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}</m>. Since <m>\langle X \rangle</m> is a subgroup that contains <m>X</m>, it is closed under products and inverses, and thus must contain all elements of <m>S</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  For the opposite containment, we just need to show the set <m>S</m> really is a subgroup. We use the one step test:
                </p>
        
                <p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>S \ne \emptyset</m> since we allow <m>m = 0</m> and declare the empty product to be <m>e_G</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
        
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}</m> and <m>y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m}</m> are in <m>S</m> then 
                        <me>
                          x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}(y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m})^{-1}=x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} y_n^{-i_m} \cdots y_1^{-i_1}
                        </me> 
                        is also in <m>S</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </p>
          
                  <p>
                    Therefore <m>S\leq G</m> and <m>X\subseteq S</m> (by taking <m>m=1</m> and <m>j_1=1</m>) and by the minimality of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> we obtain <m>\langle X \rangle\subseteq S</m>.
                  </p>
              </proof>
            </lemma>

            <problem>
              <p>
                The Lemma implies that for an element <m>x</m> of a group <m>G</m>, <m>\langle x\rangle=\{x^j \mid j\in \mathbb{Z}\}</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Verify <m>D_{2n}=\langle r,s \rangle</m>, meaning that <m>D_{2n}</m> is the subgroup of <m>D_{2n}</m> generated by <m>\{r,s\}</m>.
              </p>
            </problem>

            <problem>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A_n</m> is the subgroup of <m>S_n</m> generated by all produts of <m>2</m>-cyclies (disjoint or not). In symbols, 
                <me>
                  A_n=\langle (i \ j )(k \ l) \mid i,j,k,l \in \{1, \ldots, n\}\rangle.
                </me>
                
              </p>
            </problem>


            <problem>
              <p>
                Consider the set <m>\mu=\{z\in \C \setminus \{0\} \mid z^n = 1 \text{ for some integer }n \geq 1\}</m>, which is a subgroup of <m>( \C \setminus \{0\} , \cdot)</m> (a fact you need not prove).
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that for each integer <m>m \geq 1</m>, there is a unique subgroup <m>H_m\leq \mu</m> with <m>|H_m|=m</m> and that <m>H_m</m> is cyclic. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that every finitely generated subgroup of <m>\mu</m> has finitely many elements. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that <m>\mu</m> is not finitely generated.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </problem>

          </subsection>

        </section>
      </chapter> 

      <chapter xml:id="gp-homs">
        <title>Homomorphisms and Isomorphisms</title>

        <section xml:id="sec-gphoms">
          <title>Group Homomorphisms</title>
          

          <definition xml:id="def-gphom">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>G</m> and <m>H</m> are groups, a <em>homomorphism</em> from <m>G</m> is <m>H</m> is a function <m>f: G \to H</m> such that <m>f(x \cdot_G y) = f(x) \cdot_H f(y)</m>, where <m>\cdot_G</m> and <m>\cdot_H</m> denote the multiplication rules for <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>, respectively.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Prove the following
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The identity map is a group isomomorphism for any group <m>G</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The exponential map <m>\exp: ({\mathbb{R}}, +) \to ({\mathbb{R}}\setminus \{0\}, \cdot)</m> is a homomorphism. So is <m>\ln: ({\mathbb{R}}_{&gt;0}, \cdot) \to ({\mathbb{R}}, +)</m>. In fact, these maps are inverse to each other so we obtain an isomorphism . <m>({\mathbb{R}}, +)\cong ({\mathbb{R}}_{&gt;0}, \cdot)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    For any positive integer <m>n</m> and field <m>F</m>, the map determinant map <m>\det: \operatorname{GL}_n(F) \to (F \setminus \{0\}, \cdot)</m> is a group homomorphism.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </example>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-grphomom-prop">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups, then
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(e_G) = e_H</m> and
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(x^{-1}) = f(x)^{-1}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-unique-Z-homom">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group. Prove there exists a unique group homomorphism <m>\varphi:G\to\Z</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <definition xml:id="def-gpker">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\varphi: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups. The <em>kernel</em> of <m>\varphi</m> is the set 
                <me>
                  \ker(\varphi) := \{g\in G \mid \varphi(g)=e_H\}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-gpimage">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\varphi: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups. The <em>image</em> of <m>\varphi</m> is the set 
                <me>
                  \im(\varphi) := \{\varphi(g) \mid g \in G\}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-homsubgp">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>f: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups, then the set-theoretic image of <m>f</m> is a subgroup of <m>H</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>f: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups, then the kernel of <m>f</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that if <m>f:G\to H</m> is a group homomorphism and <m>K\leq H</m> then the preimage of <m>K</m>, defined as <m>f^{-1}(K)=\{g\in G | f(g)\in K\}</m>, is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-grptrivialkernel">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A group homomorphism <m>f: G \to H</m> is injective if and only if <m>\operatorname{ker}(f) = \{e_G\}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A group homomorphism <m>f: G \to H</m> is surjective if and only if <m>\operatorname{im}(f) = H</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
                 

          <problem>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Find, with justification, an injective group homomorphism <m>f:S_n \to \GL_n(\R)</m>.
                </li>

                <li>
                  Find, with justification, an injective group homomorphism <m>g:D_{2n}\to S_n</m>.
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </problem>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-gpisos">
          <title>Group Isomorphisms</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-gpiso">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A homomorphism <m>f: G \to H</m> is called an <em>isomorphism</em> if there exists a homomorphism <m>g: H \to G</m> such that <m>f \circ g = \text{id}_H</m> and <m>g \circ f = \text{id}_G</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                If <m>f:G\to H</m> is an isomorphism, <m>G</m> and <m>H</m> are called <em>isomorphic</em>, written <m>G\cong H</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            I have defined the notion of isomorphism in Definition <xref ref="def-gpiso" /> differently than given in the textbook. The reason is that the correct meaning of the word <q>isomorphism</q> in any context (sets, groups, rings, fields, topological spaces, whatever) is always <q>a morphism that has a two-sided inverse</q>. In many contexts, such as sets, groups, rings and fields this turns out to be equivalent to the notion of being <q>one-to-one and onto</q>. But there are contexts in which this is not the case. For example a one-to-one and onto continuous map of topological spaces need not be a homeomorphism. (A homeomorphism is a term one uses for isomorphism of topological spaces, for historical reasons.)
          </remark>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-iso-def">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Suppose <m>f: G \to H</m> is a group homomorphism. Then <m>f</m> an isomorphism if and only if <m>f</m> is bijective (one-to-one and onto).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <definition xml:id="def-iso-inv">
            <statement>
              <p>
                An <em>isomorphism invariant</em> is a property <m>P</m> such that whenever <m>G \cong H</m> and <m>G</m> has <m>P</m> then <m>H</m> has <m>P</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-iso-inv">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The following are isomorphism invariants:
              </p>

              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      the order of the group,
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      the set of orders of elements in the group,
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      being abelian,
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      the order of the center of the group,
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      being finitely generated,
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Decide whether the groups <m>Q_8</m> and <m>D_8</m> are isomorphic or not, with justification.
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>S_n\cong S_m</m> if and only if <m>n=m</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbb{Z}/6\ncong S_3</m>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>D_{24}\ncong S_4</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              
            </p>
          </problem>

          <definition xml:id="def-gp-automorphism">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group. An isomorphism <m>\phi:G\to G</m> is called an <em>automorphism</em> of <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Prove that the set of automorphisms of <m>G</m>, denoted <m>\operatorname{Aut}(G)</m>, is a group under composition.
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be a group. Prove that the map <m>f:G\to G</m> given by <m>f(a)=a^{-1}</m> for all <m>a\in G</m> is an automorphism if and only if <m>G</m> is abelian.
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>x\in G</m>. Define a map <m>\psi_x:G\to G</m> by <m>\psi_x(a)=xax^{-1}</m> for all <m>a\in G</m>. 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that <m>\psi_x\in \operatorname{Aut}(G)</m> for all <m>x\in G</m>. 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that <m>\{\psi_x\mid x\in G\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>\operatorname{Aut}(G)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </problem>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Prove that if groups <m>G</m> and <m>H</m> are isomorphic then: 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>Z(G)\cong Z(H)</m> and 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\Aut(G)\cong \Aut(H)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </problem>
        

          <problem>
            <p>
              Find an example of groups <m>G,H</m> such that there is an isomorphism <m>G\times H\cong G</m> but <m>H</m> is not trivial. Note: since <m>G\times H\cong G</m> can be rewritten as <m>G\times H\cong G\times \{e\}</m>, the above shows that in general one cannot cancel groups in isomorphisms between direct products.
            </p>
          </problem>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-cylic-homoms">
          <title>Cyclic Groups: Revisited</title>

          <problem>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>m,n</m> are positive integers such that <m>\gcd(m,n)=1</m> then there is a group isomorphism <m>C_{mn}=C_m\times C_n</m>.
            </p>
          </problem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-cyclic-relprime">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G=\langle x\rangle</m>, where <m>x</m> has finite order <m>n</m>. Then
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>G=\{e,x,\ldots,x^{n-1}\}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      There is a bijection 
                        <me>
                          \Psi : \{\text{divisors of } |G|\} \to \{\text{subgroups of } G\} \text{ given by } \Psi(d) = \langle x^{\frac{|G|}{d}}  \rangle
                        </me> 
                        for each divisor <m>d</m> of <m>|G|</m>. Moreover, for each subgroup <m>H</m> of <m>G</m>, <m>\Psi^{-1}(H) = |H|</m>. In particular, all subgroups of <m>G</m> are cyclic and there is a unique subgroup of each order.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-ump-cyclic">
            <title>Universal Mapping Property (UMP) for Cyclic Groups</title>
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Assume <m>G = \langle x \rangle</m> and let <m>H</m> be any group. If <m>|x| = n &lt; \infty</m>, then for each <m>y \in H</m> such that <m>y^n = e</m>, there is a unique group homomorphism <me>f: G \to H</me> such that <m>f(x) = y</m>. If <m>|x| = \infty</m>, then for each <m>y \in H</m>, there is a unique group homomorphism <me>f: G \to H</me> such that <m>f(x) = y</m>. In both cases this unique group homomorphism is given by <m>f(x^i)=y^i</m> for any <m>i</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <remark>
            This is a particular case of the universal mapping property of a presentation (which we will covered later), since a cyclic group is either presented by <m>\langle x | x^n = e \rangle</m> or <m>\langle x \mid  -\rangle</m>.
          </remark>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-cyclic-classification">
            <title>Classification Theorem for Cyclic Groups</title>
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every infinite cyclic group is isomorphic to <m>C_\infty</m>. Every cyclic group of order <m>n</m> is isomorphic to <m>C_n</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </section>

      </chapter>

      <chapter xml:id="quotient-groups">
        <title>Quotient Groups</title>

        <section xml:id="sec-cosets">
          <title>Cosets and Equivalence Relations</title>
          
          <definition xml:id="def-coset">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For any <m>N\leq G</m> and any g\in G let 
                <me>
                  gN=\{gn|n\in N\}\;\text{and}\; Ng=\{ng|n\in N\}
                </me>
                be defined as a <em>left coset</em> and <em>right coset</em> of <m>N</m> in <m>G</m>, respectfully.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-cosetfacts">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>H \leq G</m>. The following facts about left cosets are equivalent for <m>x,y \in G</m>:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> belong to the same left coset of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>,
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>x = yh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m>,
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>y = xh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m>,
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>y^{-1}x \in H</m>,
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>x^{-1}y \in H</m>,
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>xH = yH</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-cosetpartition">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For <m>H \leq G</m>, the collection of left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> form a partition of <m>G</m>, and similarly for the collection of right cosets. That is,

                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      for all <m>x,y \in G</m>, either <m>xH = yH</m> or <m>xH \cap yH = \emptyset</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\bigcup_{x\in G} xH=G</m>,                    
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\bigcup_{x\in G} xH=G</m>,                    
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                and similarly for right cosets. Moreover all left and right cosets have the same cardinality: <m>|xH| = |Hx|=|H|</m> for any <m>x\in G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-left-right-cosets">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>G</m> is a finite group and <m>H \leq G</m>, then 
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned}
                  |G| &amp; = |H| \cdot (\text{the number of left cosets of $H$ in $G$}) \\
                  &amp; = |H| \cdot (\text{the number of right cosets of $H$ in $G$}). \\
                  \end{aligned}
                </me> 
                In particular the number of left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> is equal to the number of right cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-lagrange">
            <title>Lagrange's Theorem</title>
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of a finite group <m>G</m>, then <m>|H|</m> divides <m>|G|</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-lagrange">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>x\in G</m> and <m>G</m> is a finite group, then <m>|x|</m> divides <m>|G|</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </section>

